    "updated_at": "2016-04-19T18:22:41Z",
    "body": "@cossacksman You can disable/enable user based window controls for events like `maximize` with [`setMinimizable`](http://electron.atom.io/docs/v0.37.6/api/browser-window/#winsetminimizableminimizable-os-x-windows), [`setMaximizable`](http://electron.atom.io/docs/v0.37.6/api/browser-window/#winsetmaximizablemaximizable-os-x-windows), [`setClosable`](http://electron.atom.io/docs/v0.37.6/api/browser-window/#winsetclosableclosable-os-x-windows) and [`setFullScreenable`](http://electron.atom.io/docs/v0.37.6/api/browser-window/#winsetfullscreenablefullscreenable).\n\nHowever you can't prevent `maximize` events that are fired programmatically. You should prevent this by improving your code or by creating a central piece of code who decides if you can `maximize` the current window. \n\nI don't know if by setting `setMaximizable` to `false` prevents the window from maximizing when you click the titlebar on Windows, because i'm on OSX, but you could try and I would like to know the result :)\n\nI understand what you are trying to do with the `beforemaximize` events and i could see use cases where that would be helpfull (for example: 'are you sure you want to close this unsaved file?')\n\nI would like to know what others are thinking about those events.\n"
  },
